  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pricing power:</strong> If state regulators approve steeper premium hikes faster than expected.</li>
    <li><strong>Float investment income:</strong> Higher interest rates for longer dramatically boost the yield on their investment portfolio (float).</li>
    <li><strong>Telematics advantage:</strong> Progressive's Snapshot program gives them superior risk-pricing data compared to legacy competitors.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Severity inflation:</strong> Rising costs for vehicle repairs, parts, and litigation can outpace premium increases.</li>
    <li><strong>Catastrophe losses:</strong> Unexpectedly severe weather events (hurricanes, storms) resulting in outsized claims payouts.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory pushback:</strong> State insurance departments denying or delaying necessary rate increases to match inflation.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the discount rate {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. Derived mathematically, the 10-year Treasury yields {(treasuryRate * 100).toFixed(2)}%. The historical equity risk premium is ~5.5%. For a company with Progressive's low beta ({beta.toFixed(2)}), CAPM yields ~{(calculatedDiscountRate * 100).toFixed(2)}%. We use {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% as a sensible requirement.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

